{
  "project": "fixture-shop",
  "title": "Webhook HMAC Signature Verification in verify.php",
  "slug": "webhook-hmac-signature-verification",
  "date": "2026-07-17",
  "depth": "intro",
  "concepts": [
    {
      "name": "HMAC Signature Verification",
      "definition": "A method of authenticating a message by computing a keyed cryptographic hash (HMAC) over the message body using a shared secret, then comparing the result to a hash the sender included with the request. If the hashes match, the message is genuine and was not tampered with in transit."
    },
    {
      "name": "Constant-Time Comparison",
      "definition": "A string comparison that always executes in the same amount of time regardless of where the inputs differ, preventing timing attacks in which an attacker deduces the correct value one byte at a time by measuring how quickly the comparison returns."
    }
  ],
  "files": ["src/verify.php"],
  "commit": "3a81733",
  "sources": [],
  "lesson": "The `verify()` function in `src/verify.php` decides whether an incoming webhook really came from the payment gateway. It recomputes an [[fixture-shop/_glossary#HMAC Signature Verification|HMAC-SHA256 signature]] over the raw request payload using the shared secret, then compares that against the signature header the sender provided. The comparison uses PHP's `hash_equals()`, a [[fixture-shop/_glossary#Constant-Time Comparison|constant-time comparison]], so an attacker cannot learn the correct signature byte by byte from response timing."
}

